1
00:03:09,879 --> 00:03:14,350
Hello.
My name's Forrest. Forrest Gump.

2
00:03:20,039 --> 00:03:21,871
Do you want a chocolate?

3
00:03:24,199 --> 00:03:28,556
I could eat
about a million and a half of these.

4
00:03:28,639 --> 00:03:33,349
My mama always said
life was like a box of chocolates.

5
00:03:35,719 --> 00:03:39,030
You never know
what you're going to get.

6
00:03:45,319 --> 00:03:48,073
Those must be comfortable shoes.

7
00:03:48,159 --> 00:03:52,949
I bet you could walk all day in shoes
like that and not feel a thing.

8
00:03:55,439 --> 00:03:59,752
- I wish I had shoes like that.
- My feet hurt.

9
00:04:01,199 --> 00:04:03,588
Mama always said there's an awful lot

10
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:06,830
you can tell about a person
by their shoes.

11
00:04:06,919 --> 00:04:10,195
Where they're going,
where they've been.

12
00:04:16,920 --> 00:04:19,514
I've worn lots of shoes.

13
00:04:21,319 --> 00:04:23,675
I bet if I think about it real hard,

14
00:04:23,759 --> 00:04:27,274
I could remember
my first pair of shoes.

15
00:04:29,199 --> 00:04:31,997
Mama said they'd take me anywhere.

16
00:04:32,199 --> 00:04:35,033
She said they was my magic shoes.

17
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:38,509
All right, Forrest,
open your eyes now.

18
00:04:45,159 --> 00:04:47,196
Let's take a little walk around.

19
00:04:53,920 --> 00:04:55,831
How do those feel?

20
00:04:58,680 --> 00:05:03,117
His legs are strong, Mrs Gump,
as strong as I've ever seen.

21
00:05:03,199 --> 00:05:07,112
But his back's as
crooked as a politician.

22
00:05:07,199 --> 00:05:10,636
But we're going to straighten him
right up, aren't we, Forrest?

23
00:05:13,120 --> 00:05:17,158
When I was a baby, Mama named me
after the great Civil War hero

24
00:05:17,240 --> 00:05:19,879
General Nathan Bedford Forrest.

25
00:05:19,959 --> 00:05:22,269
She said we was related to him
in some way.

26
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:27,353
What he did was he started up
this club called the Ku Klux Klan.

27
00:05:27,439 --> 00:05:30,637
They'd all dress up
in their robes and their bed sheets

28
00:05:30,720 --> 00:05:35,076
and act like a bunch
of ghosts or spooks or something.

29
00:05:35,159 --> 00:05:38,869
They'd even put bed sheets
on their horses and ride around.

30
00:05:38,959 --> 00:05:42,952
And anyway, that's how
I got my name, Forrest Gump.

31
00:05:43,040 --> 00:05:46,749
Mama said the Forrest part
was to remind me that sometimes

32
00:05:46,840 --> 00:05:51,197
we all do things that, well,
just don't make no sense.

33
00:06:00,040 --> 00:06:02,678
This way. Hold on.

34
00:06:03,040 --> 00:06:06,475
All right.
What are y'all staring at?

35
00:06:06,560 --> 00:06:10,838
Haven't you ever seen a little boy
with braces on his legs before?

36
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:15,793
Don't ever let anybody tell you
they're better than you, Forrest.

37
00:06:15,879 --> 00:06:18,235
If God wanted everybody
to be the same,

38
00:06:18,319 --> 00:06:20,959
he'd have given us all
braces on our legs.

39
00:06:21,040 --> 00:06:24,315
Mama always had a way of explaining
things so I could understand them.

40
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:29,435
We lived about
a quarter mile off Route 17,

41
00:06:29,519 --> 00:06:32,317
about a half mile
from the town of Greenbow, Alabama.

42
00:06:32,399 --> 00:06:35,197
That's in the county of Greenbow.

43
00:06:35,279 --> 00:06:39,557
Our house had been in Mama's family
since her grandpa's grandpa's grandpa

44
00:06:39,639 --> 00:06:42,711
had come across the ocean
about a thousand years ago.

45
00:06:42,800 --> 00:06:47,237
Since it was just me and Mama
and we had all these empty rooms,

46
00:06:47,319 --> 00:06:51,471
Mama decided to let those rooms out,
mostly to people passing through,

47
00:06:51,560 --> 00:06:54,757
like from Mobile,
Montgomery, places like that.

48
00:06:54,840 --> 00:06:59,959
That's how me and Mama got money.
Mama was a real smart lady.

49
00:07:00,360 --> 00:07:02,190
Remember what I told you, Forrest.

50
00:07:02,279 --> 00:07:05,476
You're no different
than anybody else is.

51
00:07:07,240 --> 00:07:11,995
Did you hear what I said, Forrest?
You're the same as everybody else.

52
00:07:12,079 --> 00:07:14,389
You are no different.

53
00:07:14,480 --> 00:07:20,749
Your boy's different, Mrs Gump.
His I.Q. Is 75.

54
00:07:20,839 --> 00:07:24,593
Well, we're all different,
Mr Hancock.

55
00:07:27,759 --> 00:07:30,557
She wanted me to have
the finest education,

56
00:07:30,639 --> 00:07:34,076
so she took me to
the Greenbow County Central School.

57
00:07:34,159 --> 00:07:36,230
I met the principal and all.

58
00:07:36,319 --> 00:07:39,516
I want to show you
something, Mrs Gump.

59
00:07:39,600 --> 00:07:46,038
Now, this is normal.
Forrest is right here.

60
00:07:46,840 --> 00:07:51,276
The state requires a minimum I.Q.
Of 80 to attend public school.

61
00:07:51,360 --> 00:07:55,432
Mrs Gump, he's going to have
to go to a special school.

62
00:07:55,519 --> 00:08:00,115
- He'll be just fine.
- What does normal mean anyway?

63
00:08:00,199 --> 00:08:05,228
He might be a bit on the slow side,
but my boy Forrest

64
00:08:05,319 --> 00:08:08,391
will get the same opportunities
as everyone else.

65
00:08:08,480 --> 00:08:12,598
He's not going to some special school
to learn how to retread tyres.

66
00:08:12,680 --> 00:08:16,036
We're talking about
five little points here.

67
00:08:17,279 --> 00:08:20,077
There must be something can be done.

68
00:08:21,519 --> 00:08:24,192
We're a progressive school system.

69
00:08:24,600 --> 00:08:27,591
We don't want to see
anybody left behind.

70
00:08:27,680 --> 00:08:32,196
Is there a Mr Gump, Mrs Gump?

71
00:08:34,679 --> 00:08:36,796
He's on vacation.

72
00:08:52,759 --> 00:08:56,991
Your mama sure does care
about your schooling, son.

73
00:09:01,960 --> 00:09:04,427
You don't say much, do you?

74
00:09:15,720 --> 00:09:20,316
"Finally, he had to try.
It looked easy, but...

75
00:09:20,399 --> 00:09:22,788
"Oh, what happened. First they..."

76
00:09:22,879 --> 00:09:27,236
- Mama, what's vacation mean?
- Vacation?

77
00:09:27,320 --> 00:09:29,993
Where daddy went?

78
00:09:31,639 --> 00:09:37,431
Vacation's when you go somewhere...
and you don't ever come back.

79
00:09:41,879 --> 00:09:46,350
Anyway, I guess you could say
me and Mama was on our own.

80
00:09:46,480 --> 00:09:50,631
But we didn't mind.
Our house was never empty.

81
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:53,518
There was always
folks coming and going.

82
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:58,071
- Supper! It's supper, everyone!
- That sure looks special.

83
00:09:58,159 --> 00:10:00,548
Sometimes, we had so many people
staying with us

84
00:10:00,639 --> 00:10:03,836
that every room was filled,
with travellers, you know,

85
00:10:03,919 --> 00:10:09,596
folks living out of their suitcases
and hat cases and sample cases.

86
00:10:09,679 --> 00:10:13,592
Forrest Gump,
it's suppertime! Forrest?

87
00:10:13,679 --> 00:10:18,913
One time, a young man was staying
with us, and he had a guitar case.

88
00:10:32,480 --> 00:10:36,268
Forrest, I told you not to bother
this nice young man.

89
00:10:36,360 --> 00:10:37,838
No, that's all right, ma'am.

90
00:10:37,919 --> 00:10:41,196
I was showing him
a thing or two on the guitar.

91
00:10:41,279 --> 00:10:44,077
All right. Supper's ready
if y'all want to eat.

92
00:10:44,159 --> 00:10:46,957
Yeah, that sounds good.
Thank you, ma'am.

93
00:10:47,039 --> 00:10:52,273
Say, show me that crazy little walk
you did there. Slow it down some.

94
00:10:54,200 --> 00:10:58,239
I liked that guitar. It sounded good.

95
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:05,913
I started moving around to the music,
swinging my hips.

96
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:11,548
This one night,
me and Mama was out shopping,

97
00:11:11,639 --> 00:11:14,791
and we walked by Benson's furniture
and appliance store, and guess what?

98
00:11:27,559 --> 00:11:30,312
This is not for children's eyes.

99
00:11:32,559 --> 00:11:36,677
Some years later, that handsome
young man who they called The King,

100
00:11:36,759 --> 00:11:39,513
well, he sung too many songs.

101
00:11:39,600 --> 00:11:42,477
Had himself a heart attack
or something.

102
00:11:42,559 --> 00:11:45,393
It must be hard being a king.

103
00:11:48,799 --> 00:11:51,360
It's funny how you remember some
things, but some things you can't.

104
00:11:52,960 --> 00:11:57,750
- You do your very best now, Forrest.
- I sure will, Mama.

105
00:11:57,840 --> 00:12:02,595
I remember the bus ride
on the first day of school very well.

106
00:12:05,519 --> 00:12:07,350
Are you coming along?

107
00:12:07,440 --> 00:12:10,750
Mama said not to take rides
from strangers.

108
00:12:10,840 --> 00:12:12,750
This is the bus to school.

109
00:12:15,639 --> 00:12:20,588
- I'm Forrest, Forrest Gump.
- I'm Dorothy Harris.

110
00:12:20,679 --> 00:12:22,830
Well, now we ain't strangers anymore.

111
00:12:35,399 --> 00:12:37,788
This seat's taken.

112
00:12:39,320 --> 00:12:41,150
It's taken.

113
00:12:48,279 --> 00:12:50,110
You can't sit here.

114
00:12:52,480 --> 00:12:55,677
You know, it's funny what
a young man recollects,

115
00:12:55,759 --> 00:12:58,432
'cause I don't remember being born.

116
00:12:58,519 --> 00:13:01,477
I don't recall what I got
for my first Christmas,

117
00:13:01,559 --> 00:13:05,109
and I don't know when I went
on my first outdoor picnic,

118
00:13:05,200 --> 00:13:08,988
but I do remember
the first time I heard

119
00:13:09,080 --> 00:13:12,436
the sweetest voice in the wide world.

120
00:13:12,519 --> 00:13:15,352
You can sit here if you want.

121
00:13:17,440 --> 00:13:21,638
I had never seen anything
so beautiful in my life.

122
00:13:21,759 --> 00:13:23,796
She was like an angel.

123
00:13:23,879 --> 00:13:27,110
Well, are you going
to sit down or aren't you?

124
00:13:31,440 --> 00:13:33,350
What's wrong with your legs?

125
00:13:33,440 --> 00:13:38,070
Nothing at all, thank you.
My legs are just fine and dandy.

126
00:13:38,159 --> 00:13:40,957
I just sat next to her on that bus

127
00:13:41,039 --> 00:13:43,793
and had a conversation
all the way to school.

128
00:13:43,879 --> 00:13:46,110
My back's crooked
like a question mark.

129
00:13:46,200 --> 00:13:51,068
Next to Mama, no one ever talked
to me or asked me questions.

130
00:13:51,159 --> 00:13:53,389
Are you stupid or something?

131
00:13:53,480 --> 00:13:56,870
Mama says,
"Stupid is as stupid does."

132
00:13:56,960 --> 00:14:01,828
- I'm Jenny.
- I'm Forrest, Forrest Gump.

133
00:14:01,919 --> 00:14:04,558
From that day on,
we was always together.

134
00:14:04,639 --> 00:14:07,234
Jenny and me
was like peas and carrots.

135
00:14:09,799 --> 00:14:12,029
She taught me how to climb.

136
00:14:12,120 --> 00:14:14,428
Come on, Forrest, you can do it.

137
00:14:14,519 --> 00:14:16,988
I showed her how to dangle.

138
00:14:18,720 --> 00:14:23,874
She helped me learn how to read,
and I showed her how to swing.

139
00:14:25,200 --> 00:14:29,750
Sometimes, we'd just sit out
and wait for the stars.

140
00:14:29,840 --> 00:14:34,960
- Mama's going to worry about me.
- Just stay a little longer.

141
00:14:35,039 --> 00:14:38,952
For some reason,
Jenny never wanted to go home.

142
00:14:39,039 --> 00:14:41,634
OK, Jenny, I'll stay.

143
00:14:41,720 --> 00:14:45,029
She was my most special friend.

144
00:14:48,080 --> 00:14:50,639
My only friend.

145
00:14:52,320 --> 00:14:56,028
My Mama always told me
that miracles happen every day.

146
00:14:56,120 --> 00:14:59,668
Some people don't think so,
but they do.

147
00:15:01,799 --> 00:15:04,677
Hey, dummy!

148
00:15:04,879 --> 00:15:07,154
Are you retarded,
or just plain stupid?

149
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:10,390
- Look, I'm Forrest Gimp.
- Just run away, Forrest.

150
00:15:11,720 --> 00:15:14,552
Run, Forrest! Run away! Hurry!

151
00:15:14,799 --> 00:15:17,996
- Get the bikes!
- Let's get him! Come on!

152
00:15:18,080 --> 00:15:22,630
Look out, dummy!
We're going to get you!

153
00:15:22,720 --> 00:15:26,793
Run, Forrest, run! Run, Forrest!

154
00:15:28,159 --> 00:15:30,434
Come back here, you!

155
00:15:43,320 --> 00:15:46,995
Run, Forrest! Run!

156
00:16:16,399 --> 00:16:19,914
You wouldn't
believe it if I told you,

157
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:23,230
but I can run like the wind blows.

158
00:16:26,360 --> 00:16:32,116
From that day on, if I was
going somewhere, I was running.

159
00:17:03,559 --> 00:17:06,676
That boy sure is a running fool.

160
00:17:10,359 --> 00:17:14,193
Remember how I told you that Jenny
never seemed to want to go home?

161
00:17:14,279 --> 00:17:17,670
She lived in a house
that was as old as Alabama.

162
00:17:17,759 --> 00:17:20,193
Her mama had gone to heaven
when she was five,

163
00:17:20,279 --> 00:17:24,636
and her daddy was
some kind of a farmer.

164
00:17:24,720 --> 00:17:26,517
Jenny?

165
00:17:26,599 --> 00:17:28,556
He was a very loving man.

166
00:17:28,640 --> 00:17:32,758
He was always kissing
and touching her and her sisters.

167
00:17:34,400 --> 00:17:39,154
And then this one time, Jenny
wasn't on the bus to go to school.

168
00:17:39,240 --> 00:17:41,628
Jenny,
why didn't you come to school today?

169
00:17:42,559 --> 00:17:44,391
Daddy's taking a nap.

170
00:17:45,799 --> 00:17:47,392
Come on!

171
00:17:48,119 --> 00:17:53,478
Jenny, where'd you run to?
You better get back here, girl!

172
00:17:54,960 --> 00:17:57,269
Where you at?

173
00:17:59,960 --> 00:18:03,269
Jenny! Jenny, where you at?

174
00:18:06,880 --> 00:18:10,030
Pray with me, Forrest. Pray with me.

175
00:18:11,480 --> 00:18:16,508
Dear God, make me a bird so I can fly
far, far, far away from here.

176
00:18:16,599 --> 00:18:21,309
Dear God, make me a bird
so I can fly far...

177
00:18:21,400 --> 00:18:24,153
Mama always said God is mysterious.

178
00:18:25,799 --> 00:18:28,233
He didn't turn Jenny
into a bird that day.

179
00:18:28,319 --> 00:18:31,914
Instead, he had the police say

180
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:35,390
Jenny didn't have to stay
in that house no more.

181
00:18:35,480 --> 00:18:39,597
She was to live with her grandma,
just over on Creekmore Avenue,

182
00:18:39,680 --> 00:18:43,513
which made me happy,
'cause she was so close.

183
00:18:44,880 --> 00:18:50,159
Some nights, Jenny'd sneak out
and come on over to my house,

184
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:55,677
just 'cause she said she was scared.
Scared of what, I don't know.

185
00:18:55,759 --> 00:19:01,073
But I think it was her grandma's dog.
He was a mean dog.

186
00:19:01,400 --> 00:19:05,551
Anyway, Jenny and me was best friends
all the way up through high school.

187
00:19:07,799 --> 00:19:10,075
- Hey, stupid!
- Quit it!

188
00:19:10,160 --> 00:19:11,512
Run, Forrest, run!

189
00:19:11,599 --> 00:19:16,037
- Didn't you hear me, stupid?
- Run, Forrest!

190
00:19:16,119 --> 00:19:20,510
Get in the truck!
Come on! He's getting away! Move it!

191
00:19:20,599 --> 00:19:22,909
Run, Forrest! Run!

192
00:19:49,519 --> 00:19:51,875
Run, Forrest!

193
00:19:53,960 --> 00:19:58,192
Now, it used to be
I ran to get where I was going.

194
00:19:58,279 --> 00:20:01,589
I never thought
it would take me anywhere.

195
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:30,990
Who in the hell is that?

196
00:20:31,079 --> 00:20:35,710
That is Forrest Gump, coach.
Just a local idiot.

197
00:20:35,839 --> 00:20:40,867
And can you believe it?
I got to go to college, too.

198
00:20:46,240 --> 00:20:49,675
- Forrest, move it! Run!
- OK!

199
00:20:49,759 --> 00:20:53,513
- Run!
- Run, you stupid son of a bitch!

200
00:21:05,839 --> 00:21:08,593
Run, son of a bitch, run! Go! Run!

201
00:21:24,240 --> 00:21:29,268
He must be the stupidest son of
a bitch alive, but he sure is fast.

202
00:21:32,200 --> 00:21:37,068
Now, maybe it's just me,
but college was very confusing times.

203
00:21:38,440 --> 00:21:40,634
Federal troops,
enforcing a court order,

204
00:21:40,720 --> 00:21:42,869
integrated
the University of Alabama today.

205
00:21:42,960 --> 00:21:44,393
Two Negroes were admitted,

206
00:21:44,480 --> 00:21:47,313
but only after Governor George
Wallace had carried out

207
00:21:47,400 --> 00:21:50,550
his symbolic threat
to stand in the schoolhouse door.

208
00:21:53,279 --> 00:21:55,156
Earl, what's going on?

209
00:21:55,240 --> 00:21:57,628
Coons are trying to get into school.

210
00:21:57,720 --> 00:22:00,518
Coons? When racoons
tried getting on our back porch,

211
00:22:00,599 --> 00:22:02,829
Mama just chased them off
with a broom.

212
00:22:02,920 --> 00:22:07,596
Not racoons, you idiot. Niggers.
They want to go to school with us.

213
00:22:07,680 --> 00:22:09,557
With us? They do?

214
00:22:09,640 --> 00:22:11,471
Shortly after Governor Wallace

215
00:22:11,559 --> 00:22:14,313
had carried out his promise
to block the doorway,

216
00:22:14,400 --> 00:22:16,516
President Kennedy
ordered the Secretary of Defence

217
00:22:16,599 --> 00:22:18,477
to use military force.

218
00:22:18,559 --> 00:22:21,119
Here, by videotape,
is the encounter by General Graham,

219
00:22:21,200 --> 00:22:23,713
commander of the national guard,
and Governor Wallace.

220
00:22:23,799 --> 00:22:27,838
Because these national guardsmen
are here today

221
00:22:27,920 --> 00:22:31,548
as federal soldiers for Alabama,
and they live within our borders.

222
00:22:31,640 --> 00:22:35,951
They are our brothers.
We are winning in this fight,

223
00:22:36,039 --> 00:22:40,317
because we are awakening
the American people to the dangers

224
00:22:40,400 --> 00:22:44,915
that we have spoken about
so many times, so evident today,

225
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:48,515
a trend toward military
dictatorship in this country.

226
00:22:51,359 --> 00:22:52,951
And so, at day's end,

227
00:22:53,039 --> 00:22:56,714
the University of Alabama
in Tuscaloosa had been desegregated,

228
00:22:56,799 --> 00:22:59,872
and students Jimmy Hood
and Vivian Malone

229
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:03,031
had been signed up
for summer classes.

230
00:23:04,720 --> 00:23:07,996
Ma'am, you dropped your book. Ma'am.

231
00:23:08,880 --> 00:23:10,518
Governor Wallace
did what he promised.

232
00:23:10,599 --> 00:23:13,910
By being on the Tuscaloosa campus,
he kept the mob from gathering...

233
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:17,435
- Say, wasn't that Gump?
- Naw, that couldn't be.

234
00:23:17,519 --> 00:23:20,317
It sure as hell was.

235
00:23:23,480 --> 00:23:27,791
A few years later, that angry
little man at the schoolhouse door

236
00:23:27,880 --> 00:23:30,837
thought it'd be a good idea
and ran for President.

